e":"Manley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places in Devon and Cheshire, named in Old English as ‘common wood or clearing’, from <i>(ge)mǣne</i> ‘common, shared’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The surname is still chiefly found in the regions around these villages.","English: nickname from Middle English<i>mannly</i> ‘manly, virile, brave’ (Old English<i>mannlīc</i>, originally ‘man-like’).","Irish (County Cork): Anglicized form of <b>Ó Máinle</b> (and often pronounced <i>Mauly</i>), of unexplained etymology. Compare   Malley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Munley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Manley  . This surname is rare in Britain and Ireland, and is found mainly in eastern Scotland."]},{"name":"Malley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Malley  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in northern France called Mailly (Marne, Somme, and elsewhere).","Americanized form of Rusyn (from Slovakia) <b>Mlej</b> (see   Malay  )."]},{"name":"McMonagle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cahal.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Maonghaile</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Maonghal</i>, composed of the elements <i>maoin</i> ‘wealth’ + <i>gal</i> ‘valor’. In this form the consonant cluster <i>-ngh-</i> has been ‘delenited’. Compare   Manley   4, which is based on an earlier form of the genitive."]},{"name":"Minkley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Arno.","English (East Midlands): perhaps a variant of   Manley   with intrusive <i>-k-</i>.","Possibly also an Americanized form of German   Minkler  ."]},{"name":"Munnelly","meanings":["Irish (Mayo): variant of   Manley  ."]},{"name":"Manly","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Manley  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Roger de Manley had at least 1 daughter with Sir Roger de Manley Knight."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1070–1135":"1070–1135","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1090":"1090","about 1090":"umbes 1090","1135":"1135","1070":"1070","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1070–1135":"1070–1135","1090–Female":"1090–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1090":"1090","about 1090":"noin 1090","1135":"1135","1070":"1070","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1070–1135":"1070–1135","1090–Female":"1090–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1090":"1090","about 1090":"environ 1090","1135":"1135","1070":"1070","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs Roger de Manley a eu au moins 1 fille avec Sir Roger de Manley Knight."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1070–1135":"1070–1135","1090–Female":"1090–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1090":"1090","about 1090":"um 1090","1135":"1135","1070":"1070","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","lifeSum